{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f51f4ab8-591f-4484-a342-da9be398c50b","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process and collect a trace:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps                         # get the PID\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**3. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**4. Analyze** by opening the `.nettrace` in:\n- **Visual Studio** (Windows) — best experience\n- **Speedscope** ([https://speedscope.app](https://speedscope.app)) — works anywhere, use `dotnet-trace convert --format speedscope`\n- **PerfView** (Windows)\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a **sidecar** or **ephemeral debug container**: `kubectl debug -it <pod> --image=mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/sdk:8.0 --target=<container>`\n- For production, prefer `--duration` to avoid unbounded collection.\n- `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` is a quick first step to confirm CPU is actually in managed code before tracing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aef582c0-94cf-459a-b2f5-2ebdc5eab129","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide a concise answer based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":445,"requestId":"4113:1CDC41:7479AE8:8032E12:69F15EBA"},"id":"8d214a9f-18a6-4b20-8f0e-4686a6afbe94","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:28:37.163Z","parentId":"e752f790-e328-4a07-9731-1129d9f56c53"}
